         <abstract>
            <p>This paper explores the relevance of academic thinking on lending, capital structure, monetary policy, public regulation, corporate liability, and other areas of interest to specialists in economics, finance, and law, to a problem in banking regulation that arises from the explosive growth in bank holding companies. The problem is how banking regulation should respond to the added risk--if any--of bank failure created by affiliation between a bank and an enterprise engaged (through other subsidiaries) in activities that, technically or functionally, are not banking. The problem has two components: Does this affiliation in fact increase a bank's risks? If so, what is the socially least costly method of dealing with the added risk?</p>
         </abstract>
